                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d77">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/12306: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-02-04T09:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 4, 1938—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 4—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>79. In recent conversation with Vice Minister Hsu Mo latter informed Peck<note
                        n="98" xml:id="d77fn98">Willys R. Peck, Counselor of Embassy in
                        China.</note> that the Secretary of State had said to the Chinese Ambassador
                    in regard to reports that Great Britain, France and the Soviet Union were
                    discussing plan for assisting China to resist Japan, that the United States
                    would go as far as other powers in aiding China but declined to commit itself in
                    regard to any plan still in stage of discussion. The remark of the Vice Minister
                    was made casually in a general conversation but may be of interest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
